Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap alerts

[Once a horse has Eastern equine encephalitis they generally do not recover. If they do not die, they are often euthanized because of their poor condition and poor prognosis. The vaccine is very effective in preventing the disease. However, the protection against this disease wanes quickly. In areas that frequently have the disease, it is recommended to vaccinate every 4 months and certainly every 6 months.

Horses cannot pass this disease to people. It only is acquired from the bite of an infected mosquito.

Precautions to prevent the disease in people is as important as preventing the disease in horses. There is no vaccine for people. However, there are mosquito repellents available for horses and humans and should be used according to label directions.

Wearing long sleeves, long pants and light colored clothing is helpful in discouraging the mosquitoes. In the event of outdoor activities, wearing proper clothing and using mosquito repellent is a must. Otherwise avoid dusk and dawn when the mosquitoes are most active.

Mosquito repellent with DEET is the most appropriate repellent for humans.

Belchertown, Massachusetts may be found on the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map at: http://healthmap.org/r/3mzB - Mod.TG]

[The warnings of the Health Department are prudent and should be heeded by local residents. Human EEEV infections can be serious, leading to fatalities or significant neurological damage in those who survive the encephalitis. There have been 2 human cases in Massachusetts already this summer (August, 2012), one of which was fatal. - Mod. TY]
